<span id="ii.xx-p21"></span> Irenæus is called “the interpreter” in the
same general sense as other ecclesiastical authors (Cat. xiii. 21; xv.
20), on account of his frequent comments upon the Scriptures.  The full
title of his work was *A Refutation and Subversion of Knowledge falsely
so called* (Euseb. *Hist. Eccles*. V. c. 7).  Cyril’s expression (<span
class="Greek"><span id="ii.xx-p21.1"></span>ἐ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="ii.xx-p21.2"></span>ν τοῖς προστάγμασι</span>)
is sufficiently appropriate to the hortatory purpose professed by
Irenæus in his preface.  But the Benedictine Editor thinks that the word
<span class="Greek"><span id="ii.xx-p21.3"></span>προστάγμασι</span> may
be an interpolation arising from the following words <span
class="Greek"><span id="ii.xx-p21.4"></span>πρὸς τὰς</span>.…The meaning
would then be “in his writings *Against Heresies*,” the usual short
title of the work.

